10/17/2020

Introduction

Main objective

The key idea is to implicitly learn the protein folding code from many thousands of structural alignments using experimentally determined protein structures.

Results

SAdLSA is ~150% better than HHsearch for generating pairwise alignments and ~50% better for identifying the proteins with the best alignments in a sequence library.

Introduction

  • 3D structures of proteins are much more conserved than their sequence
  • Goal of SAdLSA is to reproduce protein structural alignments when only the sequences are known
  • SAdLSA does not require any structural information as input

Methods

  • Convolutional Neural Network (ResNet architecture)

  • sequence profiles generated from the classic sequence search algorithms as input

  • learning the residue-residue distances obtained by optimal structural superposition on the two structures encoded by their respective sequences

  • the learning focuses on cross-sequence residue distances between pairs of proteins displayed in the structural alignment.

Deep learning model architecture

  • Input: two sequence profiles from PSI-BLAST or HH-suite (\(N_k \times 20\))
  • Outer product of these profiles
  • Objective of network is to predict matrix of alignment distances
  • Setup: 80 conv layers + softmax (64 filters size 3x3 or 5x5)
  • outputs are transposed and averaged to last layer which outputs 22 categories
  • Each category represents distance from 1A to 21A (extra category for ignored pairs)

Flowchart of SAdLSA

DL model output

  • probability matrix converted into a mean distance matrix
  • distance matrix is used to obtain the optimal alignment (Smith-Waterman algorithm)

Datasets

  • training distance labels are created from structural alignments by APoc (improved version of TM-align)

Pure \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\) data sets

  • 695 training \(\alpha\)-helical and 121 testing \(\beta\)-sheet structures
  • template structure library: 5884 domains

Datasets continued

SCOP10 testing data sets

  • 3k domain cluster representatives
  • PAIR947 for assessing pairwise alignment quality given the sequence pairs
  • LIB593 for searching a sequence library to find the sequences with the closest matching pairs of structure

SCOP30 training/validation data sets

  • 5884 SCOP domain representatives
  • removed homologs and SCOP10 domain test set
  • APoc structure alignment with TM-score > 0.4
  • 79k pairs into 5 train/val sets

Sequence profiling

  • PSI-BLAST used to derive sequence profile from UniProt Ref90 database.
  • HH-suite used to derive sequence profile from Uniclust30 database.
  • HMM model approach gives best TM-score

Alignment assessment

What is a TM-score?

  • assesses quality of sequence alignment
  • ranging from 0 to 1
  • protein length-indepedent
  • TM-score > 0.4 indicates statistically significant alignment

Results

Aligning sequence encoding \(\beta\)-structures from learning sequences encoding \(\alpha\)-structures

Pairwise sequence alignment

Sequence library search test

Summmary

  • Sequence alignment is essentially a comparison of the folding code encrypted within protein sequences
  • substitution tables (i.e.¬†BLOSUM) can be viewed as a mean-field approximation, HMMs also considers immediate neighboring residue.
  • SAdLSA can detect non-local, long-range effects arising from correlations between residues that are distant in the sequence
